{"/service/ndnp/nmu/batch_nmu_huxley_ver01/data/sn84020630/00416150278/1908021401/0309.xml":{"full_text":"FRIDAY, FEBRUARY 14, 1908.\nSANTA FE NEW MEXICAN. MSTJi FE. N. M.\nPAQE SEVEN\nFuture Railroad Metropolis of New Mexico,\nn j Located on Belcn Ctrt-off of S&uta Fc Ry\nBelen is 31 miles south of Albuquerque, N. M., at the\njunction of the Main Line of the Santa Fe System lead\ning East and West from Chicago, Kansas City, Galveston\nand points East to San Francisco, Los Angeles, El Paso\nand Old Mexico.\n1,000 business and residence lots, also 25x145 feet laid\nout with broad 80 and 70-foot streets, with alleys 20 feet\nwide, with beautiful lake and public park and grand old\nshade trees; public school house, costing $16,000; church\nes; large mercantile establishments; the Belen Patent\nRoller Mill, capacity 150 barrels daily; large winery; three\nhotels, Commercial Club; a population of 1,500 people;\nseveral restaurants, etc. Belen is the largest shipping point\nfor wood, flour, wheat, wine, beans and hay in Central New\nMexico. Its importance as a great commercial railroad city\nin the near future cannot be estimated.\nThe C3\nBelen Town and\nImprovement\nCompare\nare owners f the\nBELEN I0WJSITE\nJOHN BECKER, President.\nWM. M. BiQEB, Secretary.\nALL FAST LIMITED EXPRESS, MAIL AND\nFREIGHT TRAINS OF THE SANTA FE WILL GO\nOVER THE MAIN LINE THROUGH TO BELEN,\nEAST AND WEST, NORTH AND SOUTH.\nTho lota offered are in the center of the city, well graded\n(many of them improved by cultivation no sand or grav\nel. We need a first-cluss bakery, tailor shop, shoe house-Jew-eler,\nplumbing shop, planing mill, coal and wood yard,\ndrug store, harness shop olc. etc.; also a first-class modern\nhotel.\nOur prices of lots are low and terms on easy payments;;\ntitle perfect; warranty deeds. One-third purchase money,\ncash. Two-thirds lmiy remain on note, with mortgage as se\ncurity, for one year, with 8 pfr cent interest thereon.\nApply at once fr map and prices if you wish to wcure\nthe choicest loU.\nThe Belen Town and Improvement C\nompany\nwar\nIN THE SUPREME COURT OF\nTHE TERRITORY OF NEW MEXICO\nNo. 1201.\nNo. 10W.\nNo. 1161.\nNo. 1192.\nNo. 1194.\nNo. 1195.\nNo. 1198.\nNo. 1205.\nNo. 207.\nNo. 1209.\nNo, 1210.\nNo. 1211,\nNo. 1214.\nNo. 1217.\nNo. 1218.\nNo. 1219.\nNo. 1223.\nNo. 1224.\nList of Cases For Hearing February 24, 1908.\nIn the matter of tho charges against W. J. Uiltson.\nSolomon Luna, plaintiff in error, vs. Cen lllos Coal lluil-\nroad Co., defendant in error.\nJohn Jenkins, plaintiff in error, vs. The Maxwell Land\nGrant Company, defendant in error.\nFirst Nat'l Bk. of Tucumcart, appelle, vs. C. Adams, et al.,\nappellants.\nTerritory of New Mexico, appellee, vs. Jessie Kimmiek,\nappellant.\nUnited States of America, appellee, vs. Jesus Ma. Medina,\nappellant.\nJessie Kimmiek, plaintiff in error, vs. The Territory of\nNew Mexico, defendant in error.\nRichard Di Palma and Bernard Ruppc, appellees, vs. J. A.\nWeinman and Joseph Barnett, appellants.\nTerritory of N.cw Mexico, appellee, vs. Victor Telles. appel\nlant. The Santa Po, Baton Des Moines B. R. Co., appellant,\nvs. St. Louis, Rocky Mountain Pac. R. R. Co., ap\npellee. The Territory of New Mexico, appellant, vs. Ilattio H.\nCrary, et al.. appellees.\nThe Territory of Now Nexico, appellant, vs. fieorge B.\nWoodward et al., appellees,\nThe Territory of New Mexico, appellee, vs. Tom Caldwull,\not al., appellants.\nGallup Electric Light Company, appellee, vs. Pacific Im\nprovement Co., etal., appellants.\nHonry Lockhart, appellee, vs. the Washington Gold\nSilver Mining Co., appellants.\nThe Territory of New Mexico, appellee, vs. Jim West, ap\npellant. The Territory of New Mexico, appellee, vs. Jap Clark,\net al., appellants.\nTho Territory of New Mexico, appellee, vs. Kicardo Alarid,\nappellant.\nMORIARTY ITEMS\nMorlarty, N. M., Feb. U.S. K.\nRush, editor of. tho Messenger, has\nbeen appointed postmaster at Morlar\nty to fill a vacancy caused by the res\nignation of M. T. Morlarty. Mr. Rush\ntook charge of tbe office Wednesday\nhist and has already proven his ability\nto fill the position to the entire satis\nfaction of Its patrons.\nGeorge Dewltt who recently remov\ned to Morlarty from Knoxville, Iowa,\nhas his new residence on East Central\navenuo nearly completed. The house\n13 well built and modern In every par\nticular and would be a credit to any\ntown. Mr. Dewltt has also completed\nthe erection of a suitable barn on his\npremises. He is well pleased with the\nEstancla valley and will make Morlar\nty his permanent home.\nMorlarty is to have an up-to-date\ndrug store in the near future. The pho\nproprietor of the new store will be E.\nO. Broeckllne of Santa Fe. Mr. Broeck\nllne has already secured fixtures and\nhas leased a store room on West Cen\ntral avenue owned by Judge Moriarty.\nThere Is now very little frost In the\nground in this vicinity and consider\nable breaking is under way. Yesterday\nfrom one point the writer counted\neight outfits that were turning over\nthe sod.\nMrs. R. O, Smith has recently taken\ncharge ot the Moriarty hotel which she\nwill manage for Miss E. M. Smith.\nMiss Smith will open a bakery In the\nstore room formerly occupied by the\nO. K. restaurant.\nHayward and Flemming, the now\nreal ostate and insurance firm, have\nan attractive office on West Central\navenue. They are well pleased with j\nthe business outlook in Morlarty and\nthe surrounding country. i\nCharles W. Fairfield who has spent\nvnc.l Pah. ,Tn, a I n Qnnta T am 1a1.\nleave Is again on duty as bookkeeper\nfor the Hughes Mercantile company.\nMorlarty Is to have another saloon.\nIt will be under the management of\nC. A, Bagley who recently removed to\nthe Estancla valley from Oklahoma.\nMr. Bagley's fixtures and stock are ex\npected daily. He will occupy the old\nPhoenix hotel building.\nARRESTED FOR USING\nMAILS TO DEFRAUD.\nRaton, N. M., Feb. 14. M. O. Brit\ntain and Frank North, charged with\nusing the United States mails to de\nfraud, were arrested here yesterday\nby Sheriff Marlon LIttrell, on request\nof Postofflce Inspector E. P. Smith,\nof Denver, on tho charge of fraudulent\nu3e of the mails, and will be taken to\nLas Vegas, where they will be given\na hearing before the federal court. The\nmen have been In Raton but a few\ndays and wore located by means of\nmall received from other towns in\nwhich they are alleged to have car\nried on similar operations.\nOFFICIAL MATTERS\nNotaries Public Appointed.\nActing Governor Nathan Jaffa has\nappointed the following as notaries\npublic:\nEdward R. Grosh, of Rlcardo, Guada\nlupe county; Wesley M. Hall, or Port\nides, Roosevelt county; Max P. Kem\npenich, of Peralta, Valencia county.\nAlejandro Fresquez, of Corazon, San\nMiguel county; William M. Frayne, of\nTnos, Taos county.\nSilver City Mercantile Establishment\nIncreases Capital Stock.\nA certificate of amendment to the\narticles of incorporation of the Guar\nantee .Mercantile company of Silver\nCity has been filed in the office of\nTerritorial Secretary Nathan Jaffa in\ncreasing its capital stock from $10,000\nto $25,000. Colin Neblett and Frank\nRhoades are respectively president\nand secretary of the corporation. The\nlatter Is also its statutory agent.\nArticles of Incorporation.\nThe following articles of incorpora\ntion have been filed in the office of\nTerritorial Secretary Nathan Jaffa:\nBig Four Mining company. Princip\nal place of business at Pratt, Grant\ncounty. Territorial agent Harry\nWood, at Pratt. Capital stock, $300,\n000 divided in three hundred thousand\nshres of tho par value of $1 each. Ob\nject, general mining business. Period\nof exist enco, fifty years. Incorporators\nHorace Wood, Charles Pasclie, John\nDonovan, J. W. Patterson, L. R.\nSack, Porter A. Thompson, D. G.\nWoodward and William D. Rusk,-all\nof St. Joseph, Missouri, and Harry\nWood, of Pratt.\nNovelty Mercantile Compnny. Prin\ncipal place of business at Las Cru\nces, Dona Ana county. Territorial\nagent, Daniel S. Mytinger, at Las Cru\nces. Capital stock, $5,000, divided in\nto fifty shares of the par value of\n$100 each, commencing Business with\n$2,000. Object, general mercantile\nbusiness. Period of existence, fifty\nyears. Incroporators, Thomas H.\nSpringer, and Roy H. Springer, both\nof El Paso, and Daniel S. Mytinger, of\nLas Cruces.\nMineral Surveys Ordered.\nV. S. Surveyor General Morgan\nO. Llewellyn has ordered surveys\nmade of the following raining claims\nIn New Mexico:\nSurvey No. 1340. Protection group\ncoinnrislne the Protection and Re\ndemption lodes, situate in the Burro\nMountain mining district, Grant coun\nty. Burro Mountain Copper company,\nclaimant. Richard L. Powel, U. S,\ndeputy mineral surveyor.\nSurvey No. 1341. Crazy Dutchman\nlode, situate In the Burro Mountain\ndistrict. Grant county. Burro Mountain\nCopper Company, claimant. Richard\nL. Powell, U. S. deputy mineral survey\nor.\nSurvoy No. 1342. Highland Chief\nlode, situate in the Burro Mountain\nmining district, Grant county. Burro\nMountain Copper Company, claimant.\nRichard L. Powell. U. S. deputy mm-\neral surveyor.\nSurvey No. 1343.. Money Comb\ngroup, comprising the Honey Comb\nYankee Boy, Nellie Bly, Chlva and\nPeggy lodes, situate In the Central\nmining district, Grant county. Her\nmosa Copper Company, claimant.\nJohn C. McKee, IT. S. doputy mineral\nsurveyor.\nSurvey No. 1344. John D. Long\nlode, situate in tho Burro Mountain\nmining district, Grant county. Burro\nMountain Copper Company, claimant.\nCures Biliousness, Sick\nHeadache, Sour Stom\nach, Torpid Liver and\nChronic Constipation\nIaxaii\nw 4 i i us\nTHE IRELAND PHARMAiY.\nSyrup\nCleanses ths systca\nthoroughly and clews\nsallow complexions of\npimples and blotches.\nMfOTs\nFOR SLE A ruling machine In\ngood con tlon; will be sold cheap. Ap\nply to th'New Mexican Printing Company.\nFOR RNT Two well furnished\nrooms fo light housekeeping. Inquire\nat this oice.\nWelsf\nargo\nCompany\nFOR ALE A second-hand steam\nboiler in good condition. It will be dis\nposed of at very low price. Apply to\nthe NewMexIcan Printing Company.\nWANTiD For TJ. S. Army, able-\nbodied, umarrled men. between ages\nof 18 and35; citizens of United States,\nof eood tiaracter and temperate hab\nits, who an speak, read and write En\nglish. Foi Information apply to recruit\ning office, Laughlin Block, Santa Pe,\nNew Meaco.\nRichard L. Powel, V. S. deputy miner\nal surveyor.\nPurvey No. 1345. National group,\ncomprising the National, Sugar Loaf\nmountain. Nanoleon. Nell Dow, Nar-\nrigansett and Mississippi lodes, sit\nuate in the Burro Mountain mining\ndstrlct, Grant county. National Cop\nper Mining company, claimant. Rich\naru, L. Powel, V. S. deputy mineral sur\nveyor.\n3 irvov No. 1346. Hazel group, com-\nprisjhg the Hazel, Hazel Fraction, Nar\nrag.Wtt Fraction and New Grande\nlodfs. situate In tho Burro Mountain\nmining district, Grant county. Whito\nWater Copper Mining company, claim-\nantj Richard L. Powel, U. S. deputy\nmineral surveyor.\nSurvey No. 1317. Rose group, com\nnrisine the Rose and Thistle loden,\nsituate in the Burro Mountain dlstdlct,\nGrant county. Alydla Woodburn, claim\nant. Richard L. Powel, IT. S. deputy\nmineral surveyor.\nExpress\nGeneral Express Forwarders\nto\nAll Farts of the World.\nSave Money and Inconverience by Piircha sing Wells Fargo\nDOMESTIC MONEY ORDERS. TRAVELERS'\nMONEY ORDERS, FOREIGN MONEY ORDERS.\nPayable Throughout the United States, Canada, Mexico\nand all Foreign Countries\nREMITTANCES SENT BY TELEGRAPH.\nJ.D. BARNES, Agent\nRoswell Automobile Co.\nMail and Passenger Line between\nRoswell, N. M., and Torrance, N. M.,\ndaily, Sunday Included, connection\nwith all trains on the Rock Island and\nSanta Fe Central Railways.\nLeave Roswell at 1 p. m.\nLeave Torrance on arrival of Rock\nAgents for the Buick Automobiles,\nchines for all purposes on the market,\nmachines for all purposes on the\nand Inquiries to the\nIsland train, due at 2 a. m.\nRunning time between th